NORMALISED EXTRACT
Array.from() signature and parameters
- Signature forms: Array.from(items), Array.from(items, mapFn), Array.from(items, mapFn, thisArg).
- Parameters: items is an iterable or array-like object; mapFn is an optional function called as mapFn(element, index); thisArg is optional this for mapFn.

Behavioural guarantees and return value
- Returns a new Array instance (or instance of subclass when called on a subclass constructor).
- Array.from never creates a sparse array: missing indices in array-like items become undefined in the result.
- When items is iterable, the constructor is called with no length argument; when array-like, constructor is called with normalized length and final length set after iteration.
- mapFn is applied during creation and receives (element, index) only; it does not receive the entire array because the array is under construction.

Common implementation patterns and examples
- Convert a string to array of characters: Array.from('foo') -> ['f','o','o'].
- Convert Set/Map iterators: Array.from(set) -> array of set values; Array.from(map) -> array of [key,value] pairs; Array.from(map.values()) -> array of values.
- Convert NodeList to array: Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('img'), img => img.src) to get src list.

Sequence-generation pattern
- Range generator pattern: Array.from({ length: N }, (_, i) => start + i * step) produces a numeric sequence of length N with step increments. Use Math.ceil((stop-start)/step) to compute length when generating stop-exclusive ranges.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Typed arrays: Array.from shares signature with TypedArray.from and avoids intermediate array to prevent truncation into typed array ranges.
- Calling on custom constructors: Array.from.call(CustomCtor, items) will construct instances of CustomCtor when CustomCtor accepts a single length argument.

REFERENCE DETAILS
- ECMAScript spec link: # sec-array.from in ECMA-262.
- Return type: new Array instance or subclass instance. Map function call signature: mapFn(element, index) -> mappedValue.
- Sequence implementation pattern: range = (start, stop, step) => Array.from({ length: Math.ceil((stop - start) / step) }, (_, i) => start + i * step)

